 **I think that in IntelliJ IDEA, Maven projects should be configured and run as &quot;Maven Projects.&quot;** 
When you create a Maven project, IntelliJ IDEA recognizes it as such and provides various Maven-related functionalities.

To run a Maven goal, like &quot;javafx:run,&quot; you indeed need to **access the &quot;Maven&quot; tab on the right**. This will open the Maven tool window on the right side of the IDE.
In the &quot;Maven&quot; tool window, you can **expand your project to see all the available goals under &quot;Lifecycle&quot; and &quot;Plugins.&quot; To run &quot;javafx:run,&quot; you should expand your project, go to &quot;Plugins,&quot; and find &quot;javafx.&quot;**

**Right-click on &quot;javafx:run&quot; and select &quot;Run &#39;javafx:run&#39;.&quot;** This will execute the JavaFX application with the appropriate Maven configurations.

You can also **configure shortcuts for specific Maven goals, including &quot;javafx:run,&quot; as you mentioned. This can be done by right-clicking on the goal and choosing  second choice : &quot;&#39;someName[javafx:run]&#39;.&quot;** Once created, you can use the shortcut (e.g., Shift + F10) to run it in the future.

